                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: American Apparel Files for Bankruptcy</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-10-05T09:59:04+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 5, 2015 5:59 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 5, 2015 5:59 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/05/morning-agenda-american-apparel-files-for-bankruptcy/" data-title="Morning Agenda: American Apparel Files for Bankruptcy" data-description="Deaths Highlight Pressures of Wall Street | Why Volkswagen Started Cheating | Valeant&#039;s High-Price Drug Strategy">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>AMERICAN APPAREL FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> American Apparel <b>filed for bankruptcy protection early Monday</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/06/business/american-apparel-files-for-bankruptcy.html?hp&#038;action=click&#038;pgtype=Homepage&#038;module=second-column-region&#038;region=top-news&#038;WT.nav=top-news">Hiroko Tabuchi reports in The New York Times.</a> The one-time arbiter of made-in-America cool has been crippled by debt, a plunge in sales, strife among employees and a drawn-out legal fight with the founder, Dov Charney. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bankruptcy would <b>wipe out American Apparelâs current shareholders</b>, including Mr. Charney, whose stake was worth about $8.2 million as of Friday. The companyâs creditors, which include Standard General, the hedge fund leading the turnaround at RadioShack, would be in full control.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The filing <b>follows a deal</b> struck with most of the retailerâs secured lenders to reduce its debt by swapping bondholdersâ debt for shares in the company. The deal also included extra financing from the participating bondholders, which would allow its manufacturing operations in Los Angeles and its 130 stores in the United States to stay open. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No layoffs were announced in the filing, which still needs to be approved by the bankruptcy court. The <b>restructuring is expected to be completed within six months</b> and the overseas operations are not affected. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">American Apparel, like many of its peers, has lost out in the intense competition for customers at a time when consumer spending is growing sluggishly. The New York Stock Exchange warned last week that the company was <b>at risk of being delisted</b> because its financial condition was so bad that it was questionable whether it could stay in business. At the close of markets on Friday, its shares were worth just 11 cents.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>DEATHS HIGHLIGHT PRESSURES OF WALL STREET</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> There is no evidence that the incidence of suicide by young professionals on Wall Street is higher than in any other industry, but sensitivities about the issue are acute after <b>several episodes this year</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/04/business/dealbook/tragedies-draw-attention-to-wall-streets-grueling-pace.html?ref=business">William D. Cohan writes in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thomas Hughes, a 29-year-old investment banker at the advisory firm Moelis &#038; Company, jumped to his death from his 24th-floor apartment in May. There were signs of heavy drinking and cocaine use. Police ruled it a suicide, but his father John refuses to believe that. He thinks his son, <b>under stress from work</b>, tried to re-energize himself with cocaine and the combination of substances drove him crazy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A month earlier, Sarvshreshth Gupta, a 22-year-old first-year banking analyst at Goldman Sachs, <b>committed suicide</b> after a particularly stressful stretch at work. Around the same time, another first-year analyst who had worked 72 hours straight was hospitalized after having a seizure. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 2013, Moritz Erhardt, a 21-year-old intern at Bank of America Merrill Lynch, <b>died after having an epileptic seizure</b>. He had worked the previous 72 hours without sleeping.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These episodes have crystallized a need for change, and Wall Street has been <b>trying to provide a better work-life balance</b> for its junior bankers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Goldman <b>banned its interns from all-nighters</b> and working through the weekend. Barclays forbids its analysts from working more than 12 days in a row. JPMorgan has the option of one âprotected weekendâ each month. Bank of America put in measures to improve supervision and ensure a minimum of four weekend days a month.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These efforts have not been entirely successful. Investment banking is <b>still labor intensive and resists automation</b>. Life on Wall Street is a never-ending push to close deals. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âYou canât really stand out because most of what youâre doing does not require original thinking,â said Kevin Roose, the author of a book about young Wall Street bankers. âSo the only way you can distinguish yourself is by sheer endurance. <b>Gluttons for punishment are rewarded</b> on Wall Street, especially at the young levels.â </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>WHY VOLKSWAGEN STARTED CHEATING</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> It started when the carmaker realized that a <b>new diesel engine it had developed at great expense</b> could not meet pollution standards in the United States, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/05/business/engine-shortfall-pushed-volkswagen-to-evade-emissions-testing.html?ref=business">Jack Ewing reports in The New York Times</a>. Rather than throw out years of work and investment, managers decided to cheat, people with knowledge of Volkswagenâs internal inquiry said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The software that enabled Volkswagen to cheat on emissions tests was installed starting in 2008.  By then, the automaker had <b>spent several years developing the new EA 189 diesel engine line</b> and was preparing for production. The cars with the new motors started arriving in the United States in 2009. By that point, it would have been a severe setback to cancel production and go back to the drawing board.   </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It remains <b>unclear who made the decision</b> to install the illegal software. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Three top managers who played prominent roles in engine development <b>have been suspended</b>, but Volkswagen has not disclosed why. They are Ulrich Hackenberg, head of development; Heinz-Jakob Neusser, head of development for the Volkswagen brand; and Wolfgang Hatz, head of engines and transmissions development.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Volkswagen has said it would unveil a <b>technical solution for the affected vehicles on Wednesday</b>, when the companyâs supervisory board is scheduled to hold an emergency meeting. Experts are skeptical  about its ability to make cars compliant without hurting fuel economy and performance.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Eurozone finance ministers</b> are meeting in Luxembourg and will hold a news conference at 11:30 a.m.<br />
<b>Ben S. Bernanke</b> is a guest on CNBC at 8 a.m. <b>Carl Icahn</b> is a guest on Fox Business Network at 2 p.m. <b>Stephen A. Schwarzman</b> will be a guest on Bloomberg Television at 7 a.m. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>VALEANTâS HIGH-PRICE DRUG STRATEGY</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Until recently, investors were star-struck by drug companies that could raise prices indiscriminately, but they are beginning to see the dangers of such a model,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/04/business/valeants-high-price-drug-strategy.html?ref=business">Gretchen Morgenson writes in the Fair Game column.</a> Price jumps may generate earnings and stock gains, but the enrichment of a few at the cost of many often <b>attracts unwanted scrutiny</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Valeantâs habit of buying up existing drugs and raising prices aggressively has <b>angered lawmakers and stoked public outrage</b> against the growing trend of higher and higher drug prices, as <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/05/business/valeants-drug-price-strategy-enriches-it-but-infuriates-patients-and-lawmakers.html?ribbon-ad-idx=5&#038;rref=business">Andrew Pollack and Sabrina Tavernise report in The New York Times.</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last Monday, 18 Democratic members of the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform asked its chairman to subpoena Valeant for documents about price increases. <b>Valeantâs stock slid</b> 16.5 percent on the news. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">J. Michael Pearson, Valeantâs chief executive, had to <b>reassure employees</b>, rejecting investor concerns about the strategy of relying on big price increases. He said that half of the companyâs sales came from domestic and international businesses in which it had realized small or no net price increases.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At Valeant, executive pay is heavily <b>tied to shareholder returns</b>. It is by no means the only company whose strategy skews rewards to executives and shareholders. That is how the game is played. But isnât it crazy, Ms. Morgenson asks, to leave everything up to <b>executives who manage only their stock price?</b><br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
